    <section class="row">
      <h4>Description</h4>
      <p>Students use pattern blocks as area models to compare fractional regions and explore how the regions change in relation to the whole.</p>

      <h4>Mathematics</h4>
      <p>Students need to understand that a fractional unit can be represented flexibly depending on the amount of the whole. For example, one green triangle is <abbr title="One Sixth" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>6</sub></span></abbr>
        of the whole if one hexagon is the whole. If one hexagon equals 3 wholes, then one green triangle equals <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>. This flexibility
        and proportional reasoning is important to understanding fractions. Students benefit from opportunities to compose and decompose fractions (using both concrete models and symbolic representations) to compare fractional parts and recognize
        equivalent fractions. Answers may include repeated addition and/or multiplication of unit fractions.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <h4>Curriculum Connections</h4>
      <p>Students will:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>determine the relationship between fractional parts and the whole</li>
        <li>represent fractions using models and symbols</li>
        <li>find equivalent fractions using concrete materials</li>
        <li>compare fractions symbolically and with models by considering the fractional unit</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <h4>Instructional Sequence</h4>
      <ol>
        <li>Partner students and provide each pair with <abbr title="Blackline Master">BLM</abbr> 1 and pattern blocks.</li>
        <li>Allow students to use the pattern blocks to solve each of the problems. Note: You might decide to sequence the tasks in an intentional order depending on student familiarity with fractions and/or using pattern blocks in a fractions
          context. Since students often use the yellow hexagon as one whole, starting with the yellow hexagon equal to three wholes disrupts this persistent notion.</li>
        <li>Some discussion about ratios including part-part relationships may be necessary for the final task, which could alternatively be an extension question or a diagnostic opportunity.</li>
        <li>Consolidate by selecting student responses which highlight a range of strategies and discussing as a class. Create an anchor chart to share successful strategies.</li>
        <li>To extend: Have each pair of students make up a set of questions for another pair to solve. They could choose another shape as the whole.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="row">
      <div class="col-sm-6 col-md-6 no-padding-left">
        <h4>Highlights of Student Thinking</h4>
        <p>Students may:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>physically layer pattern blocks to make comparisons</li>
          <li>draw or manipulate the shapes using repeated addition to solve (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr>, 1 <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> = <abbr
              title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> + <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> +
            <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> or 3 x <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr>)</li>
          <li>identify the fraction unit (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr>, <abbr title="one half" class="abbr-frac"><span class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>2</sub></span></abbr> , <abbr title="one sixth" class="abbr-frac"><span
                class="frac"><sup>1</sup><span>&frasl;</span><sub>6</sub></span></abbr> ) by considering the relationship between the whole and one pattern block</li>
          <li>demonstrate spatial reasoning, geometric thinking, and/or proportional reasoning</li>
          <li>write equivalent fractions</li>
          <li>use unit fractions to add up to one whole to prove their answer</li>
          <li>switch to set representations on the ratio question</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="col-md-6">
        <h4 style="margin-left:55px;">Key Questions</h4>
        <ol>
          <li>Is there another way to say/name that fraction (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr> three sixths is also one half)?</li>
          <li>Can you show me how you know what one _____ (<abbr title="For example">e.g.</abbr> , triangle, trapezoid) is worth?</li>
          <li>Can you show me some equivalent fractions that you notice?</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </section>

